segments.text: Marshall Robinette?
Oh yeah.
In fact, they were in a special class.
The ones that were taking science were in a special algebra class that I happened to be in.
I shouldn't have been in it really, but after laying out of school two years, when I looked at that second
year algebra that I was supposed to be going into, I discovered I didn't have a clue.
So I dropped English and took the first year algebra.
And later on to my ultimate disgrace, I took, next time I took a correspondence course in English from New York to Texas.
So I had three credit hours that I made
You know how easy the UT courses are.
So you have at least some Lang Longhorn background.
I have three hours from the University of Texas.
But I was in this algebra class and we had a, I can't think of his name, I wish I could, an instructor that was absolutely outstanding.
He could make anybody see it.
And we had a bunch of these football players.
in there that were taking science.

And I was in that class and it was, after getting oriented a couple of weeks, it was really a bloody cinch for me because I've taken two years of algebra in high school and as a coach, so I had a lot of fun helping these guys through that course.
Let's help me with nicknames for various food items in the dining hall.
Cush, butter, milk, tea.
Ketchup.
That's blood.
Cedar.
I see bullets or wings, I think.
Milk was cow, wasn't it?
Yeah, yeah.
Bread was deal?
Yeah.
I'll think of some of those and that'll go along.
All right.
Try to recall and share with me some of the pranks, the jokes, the good bull that you knew about, whether you were involved or not, that you knew.
Well, I think I can tell you the ultimate practical joke that was put on campus during my senior year.
I think he was a junior.
I got ahold of one of the
make about this that you'd see in some of the movies like Frankenstein and that type of stuff.
Big teeth hanging out, grotesque eyes, the whole thing with a real clever mask.
And he was holding one of the
And he said, boy, this guy keeps scaring the woods out of anybody, anybody.
And he said, if you, he said, you have a past kid ever leaving that young doctor, that engineers.
He said, I'll get him to come over there.
He said, I'd like to come along with that.
if after everybody's asleep there, if you let him in the room, I guarantee you, you'll have more fun.
So I went for that.
It sounded great.
And this guy came over, and I mean, he was something else.
And he could fix it when he slumped.
And he had a gate that says, trouble in any worse clothes, it's even worse, you know.
And he looked like he was a maniac, but he actually did.
And so I'd go in, let him in, walk in the room and snap on the line, you see.
And sometimes I'd wake up in that room, but sometimes I wouldn't, you see.
But if not, he'd go over to
and shake the lid.
And there he'd be.
He'd wake up and look into his face.
And you'd just think, most of them would bolt.
Pass him down off.
Didn't even notice us laughingly in the hole and get out of the doctor.
They had one friend named Phil Potts.
Phil was a good student.
And seniors didn't have to turn their lights off, see.
So Phil was doing some work he studied.
So finally I turned him in on Phil while he was at his desk.
Even though it was kind of lean though, Phil looked at him.
We walked in behind that.
I guarantee you, Phil had goosebumps on his leg that were about an eighth inch high and some little goosebumps on top of those.
And he bolted.
He covered, he was on the third stoop and he was down on the ground floor so fast you couldn't ever believe it.
But we did this for two, three hours.
I've never participated in a practical joke in such a fact.
And no harm done to anybody.
Nobody's good.
Nobody.
It's funny, I thought, and he had on one or two occasions somebody attacked him, you see.
Just got frightened, just go after him, you see.
But all these guys, all they wanted was running home.
Get out of there.
Did you and your buddies as fish...
ever do any, play any jokes on a sophomore?
Can you think of any retaliation?
A little sabotage.
Primarily things like short sheeting and stuff like that, so we make them.
And of course, you never short sheet by who you were making them.
But you could short sheet somebody.
Don't mislead things for them, hiding things for them.
Did y'all ever do any drown outs of sophomores?
Towards the end of the year, we tried that.
That got us in big trouble.
Then we had, at the end of the year, we had a big beer.
Traditionally then, they'd come in these years and a big bare bust and a little lake.
Actually, a pond that was all maybe four or five feet deep and muddy.
And we'd get in there and I'd try to see if we could drive a soft horse.
This went on until my senior year, Colonel Watson, agreed that there wouldn't be any of those things on Earth.
So, the E-Company was just commanded by Charlie McDonald, McDaniels, who was a real good friend, deceased, had a fish day.
And Colonel Watson was just absolutely out of his mind.
He was just really with it.
He called everybody in, including me.
And if anybody's connected with us, I'm going to break them.
So we were all supposed to be together and together.
ranks and had a chance to go in service.
And so the order for no fish days, you see, instead of being rude to me as regimental commander,
was only posted in the company commander's box, and I never put a company.

So, I reminded Colonel Watson that if he, and neither did the staff, the battalion commanders, that if he was dealing directly with these company commanders, that he put us out of the chain of command.
Well, that made him get mad at him.
So I had developed a friendship with the Dean of Engineering, who was Gabriel Preston.
And so I hustled off to talk to Gabriel Preston about that situation.
And the colonel just needs somebody to talk to him.
He said he's about to bust about half the engineer's office.
And I don't know how to give him that, but he got it done.
And I know that at this big meeting, McDaddy group, he come and come out there.
took his capitol court on the floor.
And everybody else got off that really good, except for the name.
I think, finally, it remained that Charlie had to do a little blowering walk.
Now this beer bust, where was that little, where was it?
Physically, where was it?
West of the tracks?
Somewhere off of Highway 6.
East of the campus.
Northeast of the campus.
Southeast campus.
And this was day or night?
It was in that time.
Day, okay.
And so your outfit would be there?
Yeah.
I participated in
Well, those were not a freshman, sophomore.
The juniors and seniors didn't care for that.
No dates.
Now after that, then the freshmen took the stripes off and they were human beings again.
Now this was primarily beer.
Was there food?
Yeah, some food.
Okay.
Nobody else except the outfit.
No girls, no parents.
Just the year there.
There might be some juniors and seniors kind of observant.
Would there be other outfits having parties at different places at different times?
Yeah, yeah.
It was a pretty common thing to have a fish day.
Alright.
Do you remember any other pranks played on sophomores or seniors?
Nothing as good as what I told you.
Stealing from somebody's footlocker?
Oh yeah.
The whole gamut of hiding things.
Where would you hide them?
There wasn't really a lot of places to hide them.
You'd usually hide them in somebody else's room.
You might, if I wanted to steal a sophomore's shoes, you know, to give him a problem, I might hide them under the bed of the senior whose room I was taking care of.
Did you all play hall hockey?
I don't recall.
All right, that I know in the 60s, they would play it with a ball in the hallway and you would kick it through the door at the end of the hallway and it was kind of like kickball.
No, that must have been a new generation.
Tell me about the bull ring.
Where was it?
What was it?
Well, four infractions, primarily involved with the military discipline.
or other things, you were given a penalty which involved walking, that we had to walk it off in the bullring.
And an hour on the bullring was in the circle of ill and had somebody watching and you walked.
When did you do that?
Was there a specific time?
A lot of times on Saturday afternoon.
In uniform?
In uniform.
Where was it?
One of them was very close to where Appell Hall was.
Just off that edge.
There was another one over there.
I think in here, right at the place with Keene's office.
But after my freshman year, I managed to figure out a way not to be on the building.
What do you think the men in your outfit thought about you as a sophomore?
What kind of a sophomore were you?
I probably had a high ranking with freshmen and sophomores, because I was still a basketball player.
And so I didn't have time to wrestle as much as the other.
And also, having been out of school for two years, I was a little bit more mature than the other sophomores.
And it sort of arrived into losing to some of this was a bunch of bulls, so to speak.
And so I didn't harass the freshman years badly.
I suppose I was more popular with the freshmen than some of the other sophomores.
However, the juniors and seniors ruled me pretty hard for not being tough enough on the freshmen.
What were the incentives for you to succeed at A&M?
The depression, family, tell me about those.
Well, my primary incentive, I suppose, was the fact that my parents expected all of their children to do well.
And I often think that a lot of the parents are really, in these days,
really messing up there by not having higher expectations for the children.
My mother particularly had high expectations for us and we ended up, all three of us, from Dalvin Corridor.
I think I ended up sixth in one place.
And we were just expected to do well.
And I think that was almost everything else.
All right.
And you and your brothers are first-generation college students.
Did either of your parents go to college?
No.
And you went to high school at Hallisville?
Yes.
How many in your senior class?
Thirty-two.
That wasn't a great thing to be in the class of thirty-two.
Do you remember anything about the retention rate in your freshman, sophomore years?
Well, when the grades came out, the first grades came out, I think we lose about a third, a third of the freshman.
About how many would graduate in your outfit?
I'd say less than half.
Yeah, less than half.
Important question.
Who were some of the memorable teachers,
Counselors, advisors, staff members.
Tell me about as many of those as you can.
Well, Dr. Wolfram was president.
I thought he did a good job, particularly working with the student leaders at the time of junior and senior year.
Mr. Crawford, who had been the guy in California here, was outstanding.
What did he do?
He taught the mechanics and engineering.
Chemistry?
Chemistry.
Physics?
He was trying to think about it.
We had an outstanding lecture on chemistry.
Physics, I didn't get that standard.
I enjoyed physics, but I didn't get that standard.
English, math?
Were there some characters that you remember?
I can't remember either character.
that taught the economics, Satch Elkinson.
Describe him, please.
He was a full subject.
He could bring it to you hard and fast.
Why was he Satch?
I don't know why they called him Satch.
I think it was because of carrying that satchel.
Could be, but I don't remember.
Describe President Walton's personality
Well, he really had an easy going personality.
You could say that he could get into a crowd and fit in anywhere he wanted to.
And the students liked Tealwater.
Alright, Gilchrist, describe him please.
Gilchrist, of course, was a scientist.
And there again, he was a very well-liked person.
And he really stood him behind his engineers.
And just like I was telling you, Mr. Carlson, he managed to get that thing straightened out without all the darn things that Carlson Roberts has happened.
In the Corps, were there some memorable Corps officials?
We mostly knew the people that were there.
Like, Colonel Adcock was head of the engineers and I thought we did a good job.
Later on, after we went to Aleutians and returned to train a rather easier maintenance company, Colonel Adcock found that out in the States.
got what we assigned as engineering recommend.
First thing we do is back overseas instead of, instead of say the engineer maintenance company, but at that time we were very anxious to do this.
I'm excited against it.
You know, we were graduated early.
Not too early, but a few, two or three weeks early.
And all of the engineers went to Sam Houston.
Fort Sam.
And there wasn't a single one that wanted not to get his commission.
I remember very well, there was a classmate, E.E.
Bird, we called E-square.
And I was appellate, he was E.E.
Bird, so we were next to each other.
They took, it was the very third physical examination, including a whole chest x-ray.
And I was called in and told him that I had evidence of him.
He had some coverage.
Of course, I was begging for a wash.
And I said, well, I had no mystery of this.
I don't think this is the doubt.
I don't say I'm possibly right.
And so one of the medical officers there took a look at it.
He said, this isn't this boy that I bring.
He said, his chest is 30% bigger than this boy.
And it turned out it was E square.
And he requested out.
And I mean, he was absolutely devastating.
He wasn't like in the 50-meter war.
We did not want to.
He busted out.
Now this is the spring of 41?
What was your nickname?
They all call me this.
Just last?
You didn't have any?
Let's go to classroom behavior.
Oh, okay.
What were the expectations...
Of class, how did y'all behave in class?
Did you go to class regularly?
Did you stay awake?
We behaved very well.
I think that was part of the fact that the military students were disciplined.
The professors insisted on that.
Was the role checked?
And grades went home.
Did y'all even compute grade point ratios?
Y'all didn't talk about GPA, did you?
Okay.
Now, you came planning to major in engineering, and you stayed with engineering the whole way.
All right, looking back, what were the most important courses that you took and why?
The engineers here really dilated with the English, the economics, you know, serving very well.
The little writing in public, speaking in the hand, we certainly could use more of it.
But we were very well trained.
had you done slide rule in high school so that began was there a cut where where was the
Who taught you how to use the slide rule?
That was of course, yeah.
Okay.
And typical engineer freshman took that?
Yeah.
And how did you transport the slide rule from one place to another?
Where did you?
In the case and hung it on the belt.
And all the engineers, you could tell the engineers everywhere.
All the engineers walking on campus, they had the slide rule.
It wouldn't be taught.
They just wouldn't be caught without the slide rule going on.
All right, among you engineers, engineering was the prime major.
Was there any major on the campus that you all looked down on, made fun of, teased about?
So that almost everybody was either in ag
What was the most, did any particular field of engineering have the largest enrollment?
Was there one that was most popular?
Probably silver and mechanical.
And we had electrical, chemical.
At that time, I don't think we had aeronautical.
Oh, I bet not.
I bet not.
It ought to be silver, mechanical, electrical.
Let's talk about the library.
Did y'all call it Cushing or just Cushing Library or just the library?
And was it possible to go over there and find a corner to snooze it to sleep in?
You can try it, but it's a sophomore from the regular cruise library.
And did y'all... I had a face stripe on it.
And they had a mess off if you messed up the sophomores.
that punish you by taking a knife, taking a flat feet of the knife and hitting it real rapidly in the palm of your hand.
And it just really started smarting, you know, and raising a little wealth across there.
That was discipline inside the missile.
Did that have a name doing that?
See, I haven't heard that one before.
Would that happen when you got caught?
Right then?
Right then.
Back to the library.
About how much time did you spend in the library?
Very little.
And your academic load per semester was normally what?
And you graduated in
What?
Four years.
We wouldn't have thought of anything else, my gosh.
You spend the money to do an extra semester.
Here's the thought.
All right, the YMCA.
What role did it play in the campus?
Well, we had the other practitioners who stepped to the YMCA.
Alufin group.
Sunday evening and so were lots of other groups.
Let's go back.
You said your Lutheran group.
Mention what that was.
Well, it was just a group of Lutheran affiliated students.
Were there similar groups for other?
Yes.
Who was the key leader?
Was there an advisor?
There was, I think, one of the local pastors.
Who headed the YMCA then?
Was it Mr. Cashin?
Yeah, it was.
Red Cashin's dad?
Yeah, his dad, that's right.
Sure was.
And, let's see, what else happened in the wide?
Well, that was a place where if someone was going to come to the campus,
you might tell them that you would meet them at the Y. But it was a central meeting place.
And there was, you see, the drill field was just dying across from the Y. And there was a, at that time, a silver roof of Campbell's Park and the one with the driveways and so forth.
And there weren't that many cars.
For instance, in my senior year, we had one car in that town.
It was an old Model A Ford roadster with a rumble seat.
